      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries about the typo, I was just trying to think of a creative way to explain escrow, and I think I might have gotten a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To clarify, the person or company that holds the earnest money is usually the title company or the escrow agent, not the realtor. The realtor's role is more like a facilitator, helping to coordinate the transaction and ensuring that all parties are in compliance with the terms of the sale.\n\nThe title company or escrow agent is typically a neutral third party that's responsible for holding onto the earnest money and ensuring that the funds are released only when the conditions of the sale are met. They might be a subsidiary of a bank, a specialized escrow service, or a title insurance company. In some cases, the realtor might have a contract with the escrow agent, but the agent is usually a separate entity that's not directly affiliated with the realtor.",
